      "name": "DRYE Saturation Point",
      "settings": {
        "section_id": "mechanics-saturation",
        "eyebrow": "The invention",
        "heading_line_1": "Every other liner has a saturation point.",
        "heading_emphasis": "Ours physically can't.",
        "subheading": "Every fibre that's ever been inside your glove fills up with sweat. Then it stops moving. The rest of the shift, it sits against your hand.",
        "close_body": "<p>Cotton, silk, merino, polyester wicking. All fill with moisture until saturated - then hold it against your skin for the rest of the shift. <strong>Two fibers, one fabric. </strong>The skin side is hydrophobic - water cannot bond to it. The outer side pulls moisture toward it. Sweat routes from skin to outside, continuously, without saturation.</p>",
        "cite": "Moisture regain: Kadolph 2014 · ASTM D2654 · CN GB national standard. Transport mechanism: Fangueiro et al., Textile Research Journal 80(15), 2010. Construction independently verified at the Swedish School of Textiles, 2025."
      }
    },
